Nov. 2024

Life's Amazing Secrets

Reading Life’s Amazing Secrets felt like sitting beside Gaur Gopal Das and his friend Harry—simple chats, deep lessons. It helped me rethink balance, purpose, and the joy in slowing down. A calm nudge toward a more mindful life.

Life's Amazing Secrets

Reading Life’s Amazing Secrets felt like sitting beside Gaur Gopal Das and his friend Harry—simple chats, deep lessons. It helped me rethink balance, purpose, and the joy in slowing down. A calm nudge toward a more mindful life.

Oct. 2024

11 RULES OF LIFE by Chetan Bhagat

Reading 11 Rules for Life felt like sitting down with an older brother who’s seen the world. Chetan Bhagat’s tone isn’t preachy — it’s real, raw, and refreshingly Indian. His stories and advice made me reflect on my own choices, and how simple shifts can bring real balance.

Feb. 2024

DO IT TODAY by Darius Foroux

This book felt like a wake-up call. Darius talks straight — about procrastination, focus, and making the most of our time. It reminded me that waiting for the “right moment” is the real delay; the best time to start is always now

Jan-Feb.2025

RICH DAD POOR DAD by Robert T. Kiyosaki

This book flipped how I think about money. Through the voices of his two “dads,” Kiyosaki makes you question what real financial wisdom looks like. It’s not about earning more, but about thinking differently — assets, mindset, and freedom.

This book felt like a wake-up call. Darius talks straight — about procrastination, focus, and making the most of our time. It reminded me that waiting for the “right moment” is the real delay; the best time to start is always now

Mar.-May 2025

THE 48 LAWS OF POWER by Robert Greene

This book dives deep into the unspoken rules of influence and power in everyday life. It’s not just about gaining control but understanding how people interact beneath the surface. Greene’s insights made me reflect on how power dynamics shape relationships, decisions, and even self-awareness — a must-read for anyone curious about human nature and strategy.

This book felt like a wake-up call. Darius talks straight — about procrastination, focus, and making the most of our time. It reminded me that waiting for the “right moment” is the real delay; the best time to start is always now
